04597nam a22009495i 9780520926844DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20022003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209268447 a10.1525/97805209268442doi  a(DE-B1597)521004  a(OCoLC)1058998226  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS882b.T48 2002 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a304.2/09521 aThomas, Julia Adeney, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReconfiguring Modernity :bConcepts of Nature in Japanese Political Ideology /cJulia Adeney Thomas. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2002] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (254 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTwentieth Century Japan: The Emergence of a World Power ;v120 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJulia Adeney Thomas turns the concept of nature into a powerful analytical lens through which to view Japanese modernity, bringing the study of both Japanese history and political modernity to a new level of clarity. She shows that nature necessarily functions as a political concept and that changing ideas of nature's political authority were central during Japan's transformation from a semifeudal world to an industrializing colonial empire. In political documents from the nineteenth to the early twentieth century, nature was redefined, moving from the universal, spatial concept of the Tokugawa period, through temporal, social Darwinian ideas of inevitable progress and competitive struggle, to a celebration of Japan as a nation uniquely in harmony with nature. The so-called traditional "Japanese love of nature" masks modern state power.Thomas's theoretically sophisticated study rejects the supposition that modernity is the ideological antithesis of nature, overcoming the determinism of the physical environment through technology and liberating denatured subjects from the chains of biology and tradition. In making "nature" available as a critical term for political analysis, this book yields new insights into prewar Japan's failure to achieve liberal democracy, as well as an alternative means of understanding modernity and the position of non-Western nations within it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aNaturexEffect of human beings onzJapan. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aasia.  abiology.  acolonial empire.  acolonialism.  acompetition.  aeast asia.  aempire.  aenvironment.  aenvironmentalism.  afeudalism.  aharmony.  aindustrial revolution.  ajapan.  ajapanese colonialism.  ajapanese history.  ajapanese imperialism.  ajapanese literature.  ajapanese studies.  aliberal democracy.  ameiji history.  amodern japan.  amodernity.  anatural world.  anature.  anonfiction.  aphysical environment.  apolitical authority.  apolitical power.  apolitics.  aprewar japan.  aprogress.  asocial darwinism.  astate power.  atechnology.  atokugawa.  atradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092684440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520926844423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520926844/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles